WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.640
 Here is the one that surprises people.

00:00:02.640 --> 00:00:06.000
 A longer conversation makes the model dumber.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.000
 The model re-reads the entire context every single turn.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.280
 Early in a task, the context is tight.

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:15.600
 System prompt, tools, the goal.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:17.760
 But tool results pile up fast.

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:20.880
 A grep that returned 800 lines.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:24.120
 A file read that was only partially relevant.

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:27.600
 A failed attempt that's now just noise.

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:31.000
 By turn 30, the model is wading through thousands of tokens

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.200
 of junk to find the three lines that actually matter.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:37.240
 This is context rot.

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:39.600
 And it causes real regressions.

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:42.080
 The model starts losing the thread,

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:44.400
 contradicting its earlier decisions,

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:47.880
 forgetting things it knew 10 turns ago.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:50.240
 The fix is context engineering.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:52.760
 You don't dump everything into the prompt.

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:54.120
 You curate it.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:57.240
 Summaries instead of raw tool output.

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:01.360
 Truncated file reads with the relevant section highlighted.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:06.000
 Compaction that preserves decisions, not transcripts.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.760
 Curation has a deeper move than trimming.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:11.120
 Get the junk out of the window entirely.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:12.840
 Offload to a subagent.

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:15.800
 Let a helper burn 30,000 tokens reading

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:19.360
 and hand back a 2,000 token summary.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:21.960
 The noise never touches the main thread.

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:23.640
 Write to a memory file.

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:26.320
 Notes on disk, the agent re-reads.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:28.840
 So state outlives the window.

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:30.320
 And mind the middle.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:32.720
 Models reliably lose what's buried

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:34.800
 in the middle of a long context.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:38.920
 It's a U-shaped curve, sharp at the start and end,

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:42.560
 weak in between, and a bigger window doesn't fix it.

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:45.520
 Put what matters at the edges.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:48.520
 Think of the harness as the model's working memory.

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:51.360
 Treat it like RAM, not a hard drive.

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:54.640
 Keep only what the model needs right now.

00:01:54.640 --> 00:01:56.400
 Everything else is noise.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:59.840
 And noise costs you IQ points per turn.

